14
00:00:46.300 --> 00:00:50.060
states or even countries. And this can mean time off work,

15
00:00:50.980 --> 00:00:54.700
arranging for childcare, and significant financial burden.

16
00:00:55.580 --> 00:00:59.340
And for patients who are already navigating serious illness, these

17
00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:02.600
barriers can be enough to make participation impossible.

18
00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:05.900
But geography is only part of the story.

19
00:01:06.460 --> 00:01:10.380
Even when a trial is accessible, understanding it can

20
00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:12.260
be another hurdle entirely.

21
00:01:13.280 --> 00:01:17.240
Consent forms are frequently long and technical, and written in a

22
00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:20.880
language that assumes a high level of medical competency.

23
00:01:21.880 --> 00:01:24.620
Patients may struggle to understand what

24
00:01:24.700 --> 00:01:28.200
participation really means, including the

25
00:01:28.260 --> 00:01:31.320
risks, the benefits and the alternatives.

26
00:01:32.080 --> 00:01:36.030
And for those who aren't fluent in English, the barriers are even higher

27
00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:40.080
with limited availability of high-quality translated

28
00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:40.820
materials.

29
00:01:42.340 --> 00:01:46.320
And these challenges don't just affect individual patients.

30
00:01:46.380 --> 00:01:50.100
They shape who can really participate in research, and

31
00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:53.620
ultimately, whose data informs the therapies we develop.

32
00:01:54.540 --> 00:01:57.920
So that's why the work we're going to be discussing today is really important.

33
00:01:58.380 --> 00:02:02.310
If we can use AI to make clinical trials more understandable,

34
00:02:02.580 --> 00:02:06.390
more accessible, and more inclusive, we have an opportunity

35
00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:09.480
not just to improve processes, but to expand

36
00:02:09.500 --> 00:02:12.880
participation in a really meaningful and equitable way.

