65
00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:35.660
Thanks for being here.

66
00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:43.840
As you may agree, clinical research is under a lot of pressure

67
00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:47.260
from multiple directions, increasing protocol

68
00:03:47.900 --> 00:03:51.880
complexities, massively fragmented data silos, and

69
00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:56.769
critical human bottlenecks that's costly and rare to find,

70
00:03:56.920 --> 00:04:00.720
slow everything down. So these aren't isolated

71
00:04:00.730 --> 00:04:03.420
problems, but they compound each other.

72
00:04:04.940 --> 00:04:08.600
Having said that, AI offers a real path forward, accelerating

73
00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:10.820
timelines for some of the repeated tasks.

74
00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:15.070
It can read and understand unstructured

75
00:04:15.140 --> 00:04:18.921
data more than it can in the past, and it could

76
00:04:19.120 --> 00:04:20.921
reduce some of the administrative burden.

77
00:04:22.280 --> 00:04:26.260
But what we learned is dropping AI into a broken or

78
00:04:26.300 --> 00:04:29.000
unsupported environment doesn't fix the problem.

79
00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:30.640
It just automates the chaos.

80
00:04:32.020 --> 00:04:35.880
This is why our core principle from start is

81
00:04:35.940 --> 00:04:39.820
augmentation, not replacement. Every tool we built

82
00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:43.660
is designed around preserving expert oversight while

83
00:04:43.840 --> 00:04:44.240
scaling

84
00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:48.840
capabilities. What I will talk now is

85
00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:52.480
portfolio of AI applications, each one technically promising,

86
00:04:53.120 --> 00:04:56.880
but as Tana next will explain, the technical solution is

87
00:04:56.940 --> 00:04:58.240
only part of the story.

88
00:04:59.120 --> 00:05:02.980
What makes any of them actually work is the environment we

89
00:05:03.300 --> 00:05:05.700
are going to build around it and

90
00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:08.420
keeping humans in the loop.

91
00:05:11.540 --> 00:05:13.280
Our team at CTRIB

92
00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:21.320
organized AI strategy around four interconnected

93
00:05:21.400 --> 00:05:25.220
pillars: semantic infrastructure, real-world data, precision medicine,

94
00:05:25.300 --> 00:05:29.200
and RT. Together, they span the full trial life

95
00:05:29.280 --> 00:05:29.760
cycle.

96
00:05:30.900 --> 00:05:34.780
So what is important to notice is that these aren't standalone

97
00:05:35.160 --> 00:05:38.940
tools. They form an ecosystem, and

98
00:05:38.980 --> 00:05:42.660
like any ecosystem, each component depends on health

99
00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:46.820
of the others. Semantic infrastructure is needed for

100
00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:50.880
matching to work, and trial matching is needed for precision medicine

101
00:05:50.900 --> 00:05:51.340
to work.

102
00:05:52.350 --> 00:05:56.060
That interdependence is exactly why a supporting

103
00:05:56.120 --> 00:05:56.780
environment

104
00:05:57.800 --> 00:06:01.220
matters so much. You can't just build an AI

105
00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:05.104
layer.We have to build the connective tissue around

106
00:06:05.144 --> 00:06:09.084
that, such as governance standards, workflows, and human

107
00:06:09.124 --> 00:06:10.184
checkpoint.

108
00:06:13.904 --> 00:06:17.634
So let me talk about an example tool that we have

109
00:06:17.644 --> 00:06:21.394
been focusing that is semi-automatic annotating data elements.

110
00:06:21.884 --> 00:06:25.624
A foundational challenge across all of the work is that the data

111
00:06:25.684 --> 00:06:29.004
elements collected across studies can't be compared or

112
00:06:29.164 --> 00:06:33.014
combined because they lack the standardized

113
00:06:33.084 --> 00:06:36.584
representation and definitions such as common data elements.

114
00:06:37.304 --> 00:06:40.544
This is a data environment problem as much as a technical one.

115
00:06:41.504 --> 00:06:44.404
One solution that we have been piloting is

116
00:06:44.484 --> 00:06:48.464
semi-automatically match new data elements to existing

117
00:06:48.524 --> 00:06:49.204
CDEs

118
00:06:50.144 --> 00:06:53.544
using semantic similarity, permissible values, alignment,

119
00:06:54.144 --> 00:06:57.884
and rule-based filtering. But as you may noticed,

120
00:06:58.204 --> 00:07:01.404
we put human in the middle as number four here.

121
00:07:02.744 --> 00:07:06.364
And before any match is accepted, human reviewers accept,

122
00:07:06.444 --> 00:07:08.824
rejects, or send it back for comparison.

123
00:07:09.384 --> 00:07:11.544
This isn't an afterthought, and it's

124
00:07:12.684 --> 00:07:16.424
a load-bearing step. When a confidence is low,

125
00:07:16.604 --> 00:07:18.204
like in step number five,

126
00:07:19.004 --> 00:07:22.864
MicroRec layers surfaces a side-by-side comparison with

127
00:07:22.944 --> 00:07:23.204
plain

128
00:07:24.384 --> 00:07:26.844
language explanation of similarities and risks.

129
00:07:27.844 --> 00:07:31.764
This is a work of example of what we mean by supporting environment,

130
00:07:32.244 --> 00:07:36.084
a structured workflow, confidence scoring, and audit trail and

131
00:07:36.624 --> 00:07:39.444
clear human decision point. The AI

132
00:07:39.544 --> 00:07:42.144
accelerates and human certifies.

133
00:07:43.724 --> 00:07:44.004
Going a

134
00:07:45.364 --> 00:07:45.664
step

135
00:07:46.544 --> 00:07:50.514
higher, we have been also developing a fair data workbench to

136
00:07:50.514 --> 00:07:54.264
address one of the most structured problem in cancer research,

137
00:07:54.884 --> 00:07:58.744
data collected in silos with inconsistent

138
00:07:58.844 --> 00:08:01.724
formats, missing dictionaries, and no common standard.

139
00:08:02.604 --> 00:08:05.924
Therefore, cross-trial analysis effectively blocked without

140
00:08:06.424 --> 00:08:09.904
solving this step. So we have been developing a 12-step

141
00:08:09.964 --> 00:08:13.824
pipeline, a modular one, as you can see on the right bottom corner.

142
00:08:14.364 --> 00:08:18.064
Each of them serves different purpose, and with the

143
00:08:18.244 --> 00:08:22.184
modular approach or architecture, we'll be able to not

144
00:08:22.244 --> 00:08:25.724
only follow audit these, but use the

145
00:08:26.224 --> 00:08:30.024
tools like the semantic annotation that I mentioned previously.

146
00:08:33.304 --> 00:08:35.164
Moving into the real-world data,

147
00:08:36.064 --> 00:08:39.784
as you may agree that the clinical data in

148
00:08:39.845 --> 00:08:40.345
EHR

149
00:08:41.944 --> 00:08:44.384
needs to improve the data quality.

150
00:08:44.444 --> 00:08:47.964
Therefore, our team has been working with our colleagues at ONC,

151
00:08:48.164 --> 00:08:51.964
FDA, CMS, and CDC to develop the USCDI Plus cancer data

152
00:08:52.064 --> 00:08:55.924
standards. So can we address collection of the

153
00:08:55.964 --> 00:08:59.884
data within EHR? That's an ongoing work, but we

154
00:08:59.944 --> 00:09:03.184
also have been developing FHIR data quality

155
00:09:03.204 --> 00:09:03.944
ontology,

156
00:09:04.864 --> 00:09:08.644
so we can quantify the data quality with the published

157
00:09:08.684 --> 00:09:12.664
literature, and we have been developing some testing pipelines

158
00:09:12.724 --> 00:09:13.664
with Inferno.

159
00:09:14.904 --> 00:09:18.624
Important point to make is to LLMs are needed

160
00:09:18.844 --> 00:09:22.564
to help some of the unstructured data within EHRs,

161
00:09:22.704 --> 00:09:26.344
and we have some foundation model work related to those

162
00:09:26.824 --> 00:09:29.244
that we are going to briefly mention tomorrow's session.

163
00:09:29.964 --> 00:09:32.424
On the right side, we are working with our

164
00:09:34.044 --> 00:09:35.684
CCCT office, Center for

165
00:09:36.604 --> 00:09:38.644
Cancer Clinical Trials,

166
00:09:39.464 --> 00:09:41.764
CTRP program, developing

167
00:09:42.864 --> 00:09:46.784
tools, LLM-assisted tools to structure eligibility

168
00:09:46.844 --> 00:09:47.544
criteria.

169
00:09:48.694 --> 00:09:52.584
As you have seen on the screen, our goal is to approach

170
00:09:52.724 --> 00:09:56.524
problem from the two ends. One is, if we are

171
00:09:56.604 --> 00:10:00.324
able to structure the eligibility criteria for cancer trials

172
00:10:00.784 --> 00:10:01.704
and structure

173
00:10:02.944 --> 00:10:06.104
patient data from EHR, we will be able to go

174
00:10:06.784 --> 00:10:09.764
criteria by criteria, as you can see on the right corner,

175
00:10:10.664 --> 00:10:14.384
why LLMs are making decision that they are making instead of

176
00:10:14.464 --> 00:10:16.384
just one patient is eligible or not.

177
00:10:16.624 --> 00:10:19.224
I think this is important to become a

178
00:10:20.044 --> 00:10:22.264
functioning clinical decision support system.

179
00:10:23.604 --> 00:10:26.804
Another example that I would like to mention is the

