00:13:05.996 --> 00:13:08.376
what's going to happen during the study.

224
00:13:09.296 --> 00:13:13.076
And then also in the language that they're most comfortable

225
00:13:13.176 --> 00:13:16.936
with, so providing multiple options for them to learn about their study other

226
00:13:17.036 --> 00:13:20.996
than just sitting with a study team and reading a consent document.

227
00:13:22.956 --> 00:13:26.376
So one important thing I want to cover here is

228
00:13:28.136 --> 00:13:29.696
how we approach

229
00:13:31.116 --> 00:13:34.946
developing solutions that involve AI within this

230
00:13:34.976 --> 00:13:37.676
clinical trials ecosystem. And so

231
00:13:38.636 --> 00:13:41.656
these are the guiding principles that we use.

232
00:13:41.776 --> 00:13:45.116
So first, we want to protect from any unsafe or ineffective

233
00:13:45.216 --> 00:13:49.106
systems. So we do not want to create any

234
00:13:49.176 --> 00:13:53.066
system that causes harm or actually creates more burden or

235
00:13:53.156 --> 00:13:56.926
more work for the study teams. That is an ineffective system.

236
00:13:57.046 --> 00:14:00.066
So we are really focused on not doing that.

237
00:14:00.716 --> 00:14:04.696
We want to focus on efficiency. We also want to

238
00:14:04.776 --> 00:14:06.776
calibrate the kinds of

239
00:14:07.696 --> 00:14:10.396
AI that we're using to accomplish a task.

240
00:14:10.496 --> 00:14:13.476
So depending on what the problem is,

241
00:14:14.116 --> 00:14:17.656
we first really understand that problem very

242
00:14:17.666 --> 00:14:21.586
deeply and then determine what AI system or how

243
00:14:21.636 --> 00:14:25.176
to develop the AI to use for that particular problem instead

244
00:14:25.236 --> 00:14:29.226
of finding an AI tool and trying

245
00:14:29.316 --> 00:14:31.956
to fit it into a problem that exists.

246
00:14:32.036 --> 00:14:35.386
So we start with the problem, find the solution instead of have the

247
00:14:35.476 --> 00:14:37.896
solution in search of a problem.

248
00:14:39.376 --> 00:14:42.796
And we also want to prevent any kind of

249
00:14:42.896 --> 00:14:46.716
algorithmic discrimination. So we design

250
00:14:46.796 --> 00:14:49.936
for equity and accessibility from the start.

251
00:14:50.076 --> 00:14:54.016
And that goes for the patients that we serve, but it also

252
00:14:55.116 --> 00:14:58.996
applies to the study teams. So we want to make sure that any tools

253
00:14:59.116 --> 00:15:02.976
we develop at the NCI are available to

254
00:15:03.056 --> 00:15:05.116
the research community as a whole.

255
00:15:05.636 --> 00:15:09.196
So we don't want to keep these just internally to NIH or NCI.

256
00:15:09.276 --> 00:15:10.196
We want to share them.

257
00:15:11.756 --> 00:15:14.016
And also safeguarding privacy. So

258
00:15:14.996 --> 00:15:18.196
the data that we use stays where it

259
00:15:18.216 --> 00:15:22.146
belongs. We don't want to pull that data out into other systems

260
00:15:22.196 --> 00:15:25.456
and risk any sort of cybersecurity issues.

261
00:15:25.496 --> 00:15:29.056
So where possible, the data does not move.

262
00:15:29.136 --> 00:15:32.916
So a clinical repository with data, the data stays there and we

263
00:15:32.936 --> 00:15:35.736
bring the AI to it and

264
00:15:35.976 --> 00:15:39.476
prompt the

265
00:15:39.556 --> 00:15:43.456
AIs on that particular data,

266
00:15:43.516 --> 00:15:45.506
but we don't move the data around.

267
00:15:46.936 --> 00:15:50.596
And then we also want to declare when we're using AI.

268
00:15:50.676 --> 00:15:54.356
We want to make sure that the patient is aware and the study teams are aware

269
00:15:54.976 --> 00:15:58.776
when AI is in use and then offer an alternative

270
00:15:58.816 --> 00:16:02.776
when possible. So people have a choice on whether they want to use the AI system

271
00:16:02.836 --> 00:16:06.536
we've developed, and they know when they're being

272
00:16:06.576 --> 00:16:08.116
exposed to an AI system.

273
00:16:10.676 --> 00:16:14.376
So clinical research for cancer patients

274
00:16:14.936 --> 00:16:18.756
is done-- These patients are in a vulnerable state.

275
00:16:18.836 --> 00:16:20.595
They've just been diagnosed with cancer.

276
00:16:20.616 --> 00:16:24.436
They're struggling with long-term, potentially

277
00:16:24.496 --> 00:16:27.936
life-taking conditions. And

278
00:16:28.496 --> 00:16:29.616
we really

279
00:16:31.216 --> 00:16:34.996
want to make sure that they comprehend what

280
00:16:35.156 --> 00:16:37.496
is going on within the trial.

281
00:16:38.636 --> 00:16:41.456
So it's not enough just to disclose the risks.

282
00:16:42.776 --> 00:16:46.676
And we use often lengthy, jargon-heavy documents

283
00:16:46.686 --> 00:16:50.556
to convey what's going to happen in a study, and it can often

284
00:16:50.576 --> 00:16:54.376
be overwhelming for patients. And so we

285
00:16:54.396 --> 00:16:58.276
really need to use a concise, plain language consent form

286
00:16:59.596 --> 00:17:03.116
that improves actual comprehension which is the ethical

287
00:17:03.216 --> 00:17:03.656
standard.

288
00:17:04.816 --> 00:17:07.497
And we want to maintain the patient's autonomy

289
00:17:08.656 --> 00:17:12.017
through this process. And really that includes

290
00:17:12.997 --> 00:17:16.977
making readable, streamlined documents for the patient to read and

291
00:17:17.017 --> 00:17:20.896
understand and reduce the cognitive burden that the patient is

292
00:17:20.956 --> 00:17:24.816
feeling going through, first of all, dealing with the condition and then

293
00:17:24.896 --> 00:17:26.576
finding a study for them to join.

294
00:17:28.017 --> 00:17:28.866
And participants'

295
00:17:30.536 --> 00:17:32.516
health literacy varies widely.

296
00:17:34.516 --> 00:17:36.956
So with education, language

297
00:17:37.056 --> 00:17:41.016
proficiency, so we're trying to create tools that will

298
00:17:41.056 --> 00:17:44.376
accommodate different health literacy levels and also

299
00:17:44.436 --> 00:17:45.136
languages.

300
00:17:46.376 --> 00:17:50.256
And overly complex or long documents can appear opaque or

301
00:17:50.396 --> 00:17:51.396
even evasive.

302
00:17:52.216 --> 00:17:54.436
And that really undermines the trust that we're trying to

303
00:17:55.436 --> 00:17:56.496
have with the patient.

304
00:17:57.916 --> 00:18:01.836
And so these are the key issues that we're looking to solve with some of

305
00:18:01.896 --> 00:18:03.716
these examples that I'm going to show you here

306
00:18:03.776 --> 00:18:07.380
shortly.So,

307
00:18:08.040 --> 00:18:11.680
the first example, this is related to the consent document.

308
00:18:12.260 --> 00:18:12.600
So,

309
00:18:14.560 --> 00:18:18.160
as you all know, protocol documents can be over 100

310
00:18:18.200 --> 00:18:21.540
pages. They can be very long, very technical.

311
00:18:21.580 --> 00:18:24.560
And so what we've done is to take

312
00:18:24.600 --> 00:18:28.560
the protocol document and develop a

313
00:18:28.580 --> 00:18:31.550
consent form from the content of the protocol document.

314
00:18:31.950 --> 00:18:35.580
And what you see here on the screen first is a disclaimer for the

315
00:18:35.600 --> 00:18:39.420
consent form. So we want the study teams to

316
00:18:39.460 --> 00:18:43.400
know this is AI-generated, and this is ready for human

317
00:18:43.500 --> 00:18:47.380
review and refinement. It is not intended to go directly to

318
00:18:47.460 --> 00:18:51.240
the IRB for approval. It is intended to be a first

319
00:18:51.300 --> 00:18:52.140
draft only.

320
00:18:54.280 --> 00:18:57.180
So when we get into the body of the consent document,

321
00:18:59.060 --> 00:19:02.940
so we use the NIH Clinical Center consent

322
00:19:02.980 --> 00:19:05.170
document as a template to start.

323
00:19:06.140 --> 00:19:09.670
So you can see that the headers on the document are preserved,

324
00:19:10.180 --> 00:19:14.100
and then all the information here is in this particular consent

325
00:19:14.200 --> 00:19:17.160
document is at an eighth-grade reading level.

326
00:19:17.260 --> 00:19:21.170
And we've included, you can see there on the right-hand side, what

327
00:19:21.760 --> 00:19:25.020
you see there is OHSRP, Office of Human Subject Research

328
00:19:25.120 --> 00:19:25.800
Protections

329
00:19:26.840 --> 00:19:30.780
guidance. So as the study teams go through

330
00:19:30.820 --> 00:19:33.960
and review the consent document, there's guidance

331
00:19:34.360 --> 00:19:37.760
directly from the OHSRP so they can review the information

332
00:19:38.260 --> 00:19:42.180
and make decisions on what they need to change or what they don't

333
00:19:42.200 --> 00:19:43.280
particularly care for

334
00:19:44.600 --> 00:19:47.880
that the AI generated so that they can have a good

335
00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:50.640
representation of their study.

336
00:19:50.760 --> 00:19:54.130
So the other thing I wanted to point out here is

337
00:19:54.160 --> 00:19:57.420
that we pull from a

338
00:19:59.100 --> 00:20:02.820
procedure library. So at NIH, we have a procedure

339
00:20:02.860 --> 00:20:05.240
library with layperson descriptions.

340
00:20:05.700 --> 00:20:09.600
And so instead of having AI generate every single aspect of

341
00:20:09.660 --> 00:20:12.720
the document, we rely on a repository of

342
00:20:12.780 --> 00:20:16.760
information that is approved by NIH, and we'll pull that information into

343
00:20:16.820 --> 00:20:18.160
the consent form as well.

344
00:20:20.560 --> 00:20:23.260
And then here you'll see

345
00:20:24.680 --> 00:20:26.480
we bring in the

346
00:20:27.520 --> 00:20:31.380
risks for any study drugs, and it's in a very

347
00:20:31.480 --> 00:20:32.160
structured

348
00:20:33.220 --> 00:20:36.860
organization here. So you'll have the

349
00:20:36.920 --> 00:20:37.460
common

350
00:20:38.520 --> 00:20:41.840
side effects, the occasional side effects, and then the rare side effects.

351
00:20:41.900 --> 00:20:44.340
So we pull that in in a structured way.

352
00:20:44.380 --> 00:20:45.380
And all of this comes from the

353
00:20:46.460 --> 00:20:47.420
protocol document.

354
00:20:50.200 --> 00:20:51.820
And then areas where

355
00:20:52.740 --> 00:20:56.680
in our analysis, we've determined that AI does not

356
00:20:56.740 --> 00:21:00.720
do a great job in determining certain aspects of

357
00:21:00.730 --> 00:21:01.400
what should be in the

358
00:21:02.260 --> 00:21:04.360
consent document and what shouldn't.

359
00:21:04.440 --> 00:21:08.409
We also bring in more inline comments here so that

360
00:21:08.440 --> 00:21:11.800
the study teams know where they need to make a decision about

361
00:21:11.810 --> 00:21:15.280
which blocks of text should be included or

362
00:21:15.360 --> 00:21:18.720
excluded. So in this particular case, the storage,

363
00:21:18.820 --> 00:21:22.120
sharing, and future research using specimens and data.

364
00:21:23.040 --> 00:21:26.480
When we were developing the AI model to

365
00:21:26.560 --> 00:21:30.120
identify this particular piece from a protocol, it really had a

366
00:21:30.160 --> 00:21:33.700
difficult time. And so instead of holding up or

367
00:21:33.760 --> 00:21:37.540
releasing the tool to the study teams, we went

368
00:21:37.580 --> 00:21:41.480
ahead and just added in those inline comments so the study teams could

369
00:21:41.940 --> 00:21:44.480
determine which sections to include and not include.

370
00:21:46.340 --> 00:21:50.200
And again, this is intended to be a first draft, not the

371
00:21:50.260 --> 00:21:53.520
final version. There are pieces here and there that

372
00:21:54.320 --> 00:21:58.300
may not be great, but we retain required language

373
00:21:58.400 --> 00:22:02.050
where possible. Where it's required, legal language is retained as

374
00:22:02.160 --> 00:22:05.940
well, so we don't have AI generate those pieces of the

375
00:22:05.980 --> 00:22:09.640
consent document. And then there are other areas where we, in the

376
00:22:09.680 --> 00:22:13.020
descriptions of the studies and what will happen, we use AI

377
00:22:13.060 --> 00:22:13.760
generation.

378
00:22:14.780 --> 00:22:18.040
So we also, while we were at it,

379
00:22:18.780 --> 00:22:22.700
since we have the protocol, we developed this layperson summary.

380
00:22:22.760 --> 00:22:26.660
It's a one-page document. We adapted this template from

381
00:22:27.660 --> 00:22:31.540
a template that was developed at Wash U and

382
00:22:32.280 --> 00:22:35.860
just kind of made it our own. And so what you see here is a

383
00:22:35.940 --> 00:22:38.990
one-page document that gives a layperson's

384
00:22:39.820 --> 00:22:41.100
title for the study,

385
00:22:41.940 --> 00:22:43.320
the principal investigator,

386
00:22:44.380 --> 00:22:47.720
the institute or center, and then eight panes of

387
00:22:47.800 --> 00:22:51.460
information starting with what the goal of the study is,

388
00:22:52.740 --> 00:22:56.160
who can be in the study, what will happen during the study,

389
00:22:57.180 --> 00:23:00.260
how long the participant will be in the study, the

390
00:23:00.940 --> 00:23:03.400
high-level risks, and then the benefits.

391
00:23:04.300 --> 00:23:06.800
We also want to make sure and talk about

392
00:23:07.280 --> 00:23:10.830
the voluntariness of being in the study and how they

393
00:23:10.860 --> 00:23:14.500
would withdraw from the study or any alternatives that the patient

394
00:23:14.540 --> 00:23:16.440
could potentially

395
00:23:17.480 --> 00:23:21.340
take advantage of, and then any costs or payments that would be

396
00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:25.740
provided to the patient. So, and then at the bottom, some contact

397
00:23:25.800 --> 00:23:29.380
information, so if the patient wanted to join the study, they could or get more

398
00:23:29.420 --> 00:23:33.290
information about the study. And you can see this is very high level.

399
00:23:34.010 --> 00:23:38.000
Very high level. And that's really intended to be that way so patients

400
00:23:38.040 --> 00:23:41.780
can just get an idea of what the study is about before they jump

401
00:23:41.840 --> 00:23:44.180
into the long consent document.

402
00:23:47.160 --> 00:23:50.420
Another thing that we're working on is AI language

403
00:23:50.500 --> 00:23:54.240
translation, and this is

404
00:23:54.400 --> 00:23:58.300
sort of a new development in the last couple of months

405
00:23:58.580 --> 00:24:00.880
that we're working on. But what we're doing here,

406
00:24:02.420 --> 00:24:05.160
we're doing this because the demand for multilingual

407
00:24:05.800 --> 00:24:08.540
consent or even documents in general

408
00:24:08.700 --> 00:24:12.608
isin higher demand than we've ever had in the

409
00:24:12.668 --> 00:24:16.508
past. And so really, since human translation is the gold

410
00:24:16.648 --> 00:24:20.468
standard, the problem is that there

411
00:24:20.548 --> 00:24:23.588
often aren't enough humans to keep up with the demand.

412
00:24:24.428 --> 00:24:26.368
And so we

413
00:24:27.568 --> 00:24:30.408
brought a language translator onto our team,

414
00:24:31.268 --> 00:24:34.408
and we're working with her using AI-generated

415
00:24:34.928 --> 00:24:37.228
documents, and we're starting with consent forms.

416
00:24:38.008 --> 00:24:41.528
And the early results are promising.

417
00:24:42.448 --> 00:24:45.988
So in industry, typically a human translator,

418
00:24:46.748 --> 00:24:50.628
they can translate about 2,000 words per

419
00:24:50.688 --> 00:24:53.328
day of complex scientific language.

420
00:24:54.108 --> 00:24:58.068
And so a 10,000-word consent document can take up

421
00:24:58.108 --> 00:25:01.688
to five days to translate. And so with AI

422
00:25:01.768 --> 00:25:04.808
generation in our early tests,

423
00:25:06.168 --> 00:25:10.008
we can cut that time in half, so about two and a half days

424
00:25:11.008 --> 00:25:14.528
with an AI-translated document that the human goes

425
00:25:14.648 --> 00:25:17.948
in and compares to the English version, makes

426
00:25:18.008 --> 00:25:21.848
modifications, and then eventually certifies per

427
00:25:21.908 --> 00:25:25.867
regulatory requirements, and then the study teams can submit that

428
00:25:25.968 --> 00:25:28.788
to the IRB for approval. So

429
00:25:28.828 --> 00:25:32.648
even though we're using AI translation, we

430
00:25:32.668 --> 00:25:36.548
still have a human reviewing that and a human expert in

431
00:25:36.608 --> 00:25:40.588
the language that we're translating, which right now is just Spanish.

432
00:25:41.808 --> 00:25:45.728
And then we're providing the certification document and the translated

433
00:25:45.788 --> 00:25:48.348
document to the IRB.

434
00:25:49.288 --> 00:25:49.528
So

435
00:25:50.708 --> 00:25:54.438
really the question isn't whether to use AI to translate,

436
00:25:54.848 --> 00:25:57.928
but how we can do translation in a more sustainable

437
00:25:57.948 --> 00:26:01.828
way. And so our approach here, I've kind of gone over

438
00:26:01.888 --> 00:26:05.188
the approach here, is to generate the initial

439
00:26:05.248 --> 00:26:06.068
translation.

440
00:26:06.888 --> 00:26:10.348
We are also developing some analysis tools about the

441
00:26:10.388 --> 00:26:13.908
translation quality, and we have 10 metrics that we're measuring

442
00:26:13.968 --> 00:26:17.808
against. And then using LLM as a

443
00:26:17.868 --> 00:26:21.368
judge, so we're having one LLM evaluate

444
00:26:21.828 --> 00:26:22.988
a second LLM,

445
00:26:23.868 --> 00:26:27.628
or the translation LLM to determine where we might can make

446
00:26:27.688 --> 00:26:27.908
some

447
00:26:30.068 --> 00:26:33.448
natural flow, those kinds of language

448
00:26:33.488 --> 00:26:37.318
improvements. And then we have the in-house translator as well, that when

449
00:26:37.348 --> 00:26:41.168
she makes those modifications to the document, we have those

450
00:26:41.228 --> 00:26:45.068
modifications. So we've got three great documents that we

451
00:26:45.128 --> 00:26:48.808
can now analyze to see how can we fine-tune

452
00:26:49.148 --> 00:26:52.488
and train these LLMs to improve their translations over

453
00:26:52.528 --> 00:26:56.088
time. So again, we're in early

454
00:26:56.128 --> 00:26:59.628
stages here, but we have some promising results here

455
00:26:59.708 --> 00:27:00.468
for

456
00:27:01.288 --> 00:27:02.248
the translation.

457
00:27:05.708 --> 00:27:09.568
So in conclusion, really we are-- Well, for my

458
00:27:09.608 --> 00:27:10.338
part conclusion,

459
00:27:11.148 --> 00:27:15.088
these three tools that we talked about today, every tool produces

460
00:27:15.148 --> 00:27:18.688
an editable output. So none of this is final.

461
00:27:19.648 --> 00:27:23.368
And we send these documents to the experts to have

462
00:27:23.448 --> 00:27:26.128
them review for final submission.

463
00:27:27.628 --> 00:27:30.928
The language translator can open, modify, and

464
00:27:31.528 --> 00:27:35.048
make changes, and the study teams can take those documents and

465
00:27:35.088 --> 00:27:37.808
modify them, and then they own the content.

466
00:27:39.808 --> 00:27:43.728
The regulatory language is preserved in these documents where necessary,

467
00:27:44.368 --> 00:27:47.818
and readability standards are met, which can be very

468
00:27:48.128 --> 00:27:50.228
difficult for study teams to do manually.

469
00:27:52.108 --> 00:27:55.888
Each tool is designed to align with the ethics committee requirements,

470
00:27:56.608 --> 00:28:00.588
drawing from established guidelines, and templates where possible.

471
00:28:01.708 --> 00:28:05.468
And the outputs really are first drafts, as I've said

472
00:28:05.508 --> 00:28:09.448
before, and designed to give the experts a strong

473
00:28:09.728 --> 00:28:13.548
compliant starting point and reduce time spent on the

474
00:28:13.608 --> 00:28:15.468
hardest parts of document development.

475
00:28:16.708 --> 00:28:18.628
And I'm going to hand it over to Dr. Gulley

476
00:28:19.928 --> 00:28:21.148
to round us out here.

477
00:28:25.248 --> 00:28:29.048
Well, thank you so much, Tana. So I'm going to talk a little

478
00:28:29.148 --> 00:28:33.028
bit-- So we've heard a little bit about the what and the how, but I'm going to

479
00:28:33.088 --> 00:28:36.978
talk a little bit about the why in just a few minutes here before we

480
00:28:37.008 --> 00:28:40.188
get into the panel, which is hopefully going to be the most fun part.

481
00:28:40.248 --> 00:28:43.698
So you already heard from Dr. Clem about

482
00:28:44.088 --> 00:28:47.968
the patient experience, which clearly that must be paramount and

483
00:28:48.408 --> 00:28:50.668
really the most important reason.

484
00:28:50.748 --> 00:28:54.448
But I think another key reason why

485
00:28:54.548 --> 00:28:57.608
is the impact on the clinical team.

486
00:28:57.668 --> 00:28:59.588
So first of all, I just have to

487
00:29:00.968 --> 00:29:04.908
mention that the clinicians and the investigators, they're

488
00:29:04.968 --> 00:29:07.428
under a lot of sustained strain.

489
00:29:08.688 --> 00:29:12.128
The workload demands, the administrative burden, the

490
00:29:12.308 --> 00:29:14.208
growing complexity of care.

491
00:29:15.228 --> 00:29:19.128
And clinical trials, while they are absolutely

492
00:29:19.208 --> 00:29:22.388
vital to progress, really add to this burden.

493
00:29:22.568 --> 00:29:26.188
The protocol demands, the documentation, the regulatory,

494
00:29:26.298 --> 00:29:30.208
the coordination across many systems that

495
00:29:30.288 --> 00:29:32.857
rarely communicate seamlessly with each other.

496
00:29:33.718 --> 00:29:37.088
And clinical trial timelines are very long,

497
00:29:37.168 --> 00:29:40.458
unfortunately, and they're slowed by processes that are manual,

498
00:29:40.968 --> 00:29:43.468
duplicative, and fragmented.

499
00:29:44.568 --> 00:29:46.768
So investigators spend an increasing

500
00:29:47.768 --> 00:29:51.748
amount of time on unglamorous tasks that are necessary

501
00:29:51.768 --> 00:29:55.038
and perhaps could be facilitated by AI tools.

502
00:29:56.288 --> 00:29:59.828
The combination of high cognitive load, administrative

503
00:29:59.928 --> 00:30:03.068
overhead, and prolonged timeline has real

504
00:30:03.128 --> 00:30:04.008
consequences.

505
00:30:04.908 --> 00:30:08.028
This limits the number of trials that can open, it slows accrual,

506
00:30:08.748 --> 00:30:12.528
and it also constrains the pace

507
00:30:12.648 --> 00:30:16.348
of clinical research progress overall.So

508
00:30:16.408 --> 00:30:20.388
LLMs can perform a variety of different tasks by

509
00:30:20.448 --> 00:30:22.268
reducing the friction in the system.

510
00:30:22.928 --> 00:30:23.528
They don't just

511
00:30:24.448 --> 00:30:26.288
take the human out of the loop. They don't.

512
00:30:26.708 --> 00:30:30.628
They keep the human there, but they can definitely decrease

513
00:30:30.688 --> 00:30:31.528
the friction.

514
00:30:32.428 --> 00:30:33.408
Some examples are

515
00:30:34.488 --> 00:30:38.308
to structure and summarize clinical information, to

516
00:30:38.368 --> 00:30:42.148
generate first drafts, as you heard about from Tana, to support

517
00:30:42.868 --> 00:30:45.488
communication with teams and patients.

518
00:30:46.368 --> 00:30:49.868
